+/* This TU calls mtxTransCat (HuSprBegin, below) with no prototype anywhere
+ * in its own #include chain (game/hu3d.h, the one header in the decomp
+ * tree that declares it, is never pulled in here). Calling a function that
+ * takes float parameters with no visible prototype is undefined behavior
+ * in C: the call site applies default argument promotion (float->double)
+ * to gp->pos.x/gp->pos.y, while mtxTransCat's real definition
+ * (game/hsfdraw.c) declares plain float parameters. Real PowerPC/MWCC's
+ * float-argument ABI passes floating-point arguments in dedicated float
+ * registers that a callee reads back at its own declared width regardless
+ * of what the (unprototyped) caller assumed, so this exact mismatch was
+ * harmless there and shipped unnoticed. This port's x86-64 target does NOT
+ * tolerate the same mismatch -- confirmed empirically: gp->pos read
+ * correctly as (16.0,364.0) immediately before the call, yet the resulting
+ * translation came back as exactly gp->center with gp->pos's own
+ * contribution silently dropped, the signature of corrupted/misrouted
+ * float arguments. This was the root cause of every message window
+ * rendering pinned to a fixed position instead of its own requested
+ * HuWinCreate position; adding this prototype (the exact signature
+ * game/hu3d.h already establishes) restores the correct float-argument ABI
+ * and fixes it. Same bug shape (real, latent, PowerPC-ABI-tolerant UB
+ * exposed by this port's different architecture) as two other fixes in
+ * this codebase (an frsqrte unsigned-shift issue and an frandmod
+ * divide-by-zero) -- not a decompilation error, nothing that changes
+ * observable behavior on real hardware. */
+void mtxTransCat(Mtx dst, float x, float y, float z);
